    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Setback requirements for CM2 zoning in Portland, you need to know the specifics, as these rules are often as tricky as trying to herd a particularly grumpy goblin! They are not a single, simple number, because the exact setbacks can depend on the specific parcel, the adjacent properties, and whether you're dealing with a street-facing facade or a side yard. However, generally speaking, CM2 allows for more flexibility than purely residential zones, but you still have to respect the established \"front line\" where the main activity happens.\n\nFor the storefront itself, the setback from the front property line is usually dictated by the required building envelope and the need to maintain pedestrian access, which is crucial in a mixed-use zone. You'll need to consult the official Portland Zoning Code (the \"Big Book of Goblin Laws,\" if you will) for the precise dimensional requirements for your specific block. If you're building right up to the line, you're essentially building a very assertive goblin outpost right on the border!\n\nIf you're looking at side or rear setbacks, those are often more generous in CM2 compared to R5, allowing for some necessary utility space or perhaps a small, hidden goblin compost heap. Remember,",
      "source": "target",
